**Imagine a square stone about 50 cm tall, with a rough and irregular texture. On the front face of the stone, you would see the figure of the Headless Mule carved in high relief. The mule's head would be absent, as is common in representations of the folk figure. Instead, you would see a long, undulating neck with flames coming out of its base. The mane and tail of the mule would be carved in detail, with a wild and unkempt appearance. The expression on the face would be intense and scary, with flaming eyes and sharp teeth. The stone itself would be carved to look like an irregular block, perhaps with some protruding parts to mimic the rocks of a mountain or hill. This would create a dramatic effect, giving the impression that the Headless Mule is emerging from the stone itself. In addition, the stone could be painted with acrylic paint in dark colors, to further highlight the details of the figure. Perhaps the Headless Mule would be painted in shades of black and red, with the flames coming out in orange and yellow. The result would be an impressive and imposing piece, which would be a great addition to any art collection or Brazilian folklore themed decoration.** - <@690605468661317693> (fast)
